    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-07-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-07-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="643"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d643">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.9331/257</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Adviser on Political Relations</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hornbeck</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Commercial Secretary of the British
                        Embassy</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Jopson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-07-05">July 5,
                            1943</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Mr. Jopson</hi>: I acknowledge receipt of your letter
                    of June 23 regarding exchange of information in connection with questions of
                    policy and action relating to conclusion with China of treaties of commerce.</p>
                <p>It has been the understanding of officers of the Department who were parties to
                    the conversation held on May 7 [<hi rend="italic">6</hi>] that there was reached
                    a consensus of opinion that the matters then discussed might most appropriately
                    and to greatest advantage be dealt with informally. As was then indicated, we
                    share with you the desire and hope that the British Government and the American
                    Government will keep each other informed of any significant developments in
                    relation to those matters. We are glad to have now the information given in your
                    letter under acknowledgment. So far as this Government is concerned there have
                    been since the moment of the discussion under reference no new developments.</p>
                <p>Yours sincerely,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stanley K. Hornbeck</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
